description:
**What:** Shared test infrastructure that enables table-driven tests and e2e server testing. Three components:

### 1. TestServer (test/lib/test-server.ts)
Starts and stops the Express server for integration tests.

```typescript
class TestServer {
  static async start(opts?: { port?: number }): Promise<TestServer>
  async post(path: string, body: object): Promise<{ status: number; data: any }>
  async get(path: string): Promise<{ status: number; data: any }>
  async stop(): void
  get baseUrl(): string
}

// Usage in tests:
let server: TestServer;
beforeAll(async () => { server = await TestServer.start(); });
afterAll(async () => { await server.stop(); });

test("compile", async () => {
  const { status, data } = await server.post("/api/compile", { source: LY_FIXTURE });
  expect(status).toBe(200);
  expect(data.ok).toBe(true);
  expect(data.data.svg).toBeTruthy();
});
```

### 2. Table-driven test runner (test/lib/table-test.ts)
Generic helper for running arrays of test cases through a single assertion function.

```typescript
function tableTest<TCase>(
  description: string,
  cases: TCase[],
  run: (tc: TCase) => Promise<void> | void,
  nameOf?: (tc: TCase) => string  // defaults to tc.name
): void

// Usage:
tableTest("tabulate positions", [
  { name: "F4 on baroque lute → open course 1", pitch: "F4", instrument: "baroque-lute-13",
    expectCourse: 1, expectFret: 0 },
  { name: "G4 on baroque lute → fret 2", pitch: "G4", instrument: "baroque-lute-13",
    expectCourse: 1, expectFret: 2 },
  // ... 30 more rows
], async (tc) => {
  const positions = model.positionsForPitch(tc.pitch);
  expect(positions).toContainEqual(expect.objectContaining({
    course: tc.expectCourse, fret: tc.expectFret
  }));
});
```

### 3. Fixture loader (test/lib/fixtures.ts)
Loads test files from test/fixtures/ with type-safe helpers.

```typescript
function loadFixture(name: string): string          // raw text
function loadLyFixture(name: string): string        // .ly file
function loadMusicXMLFixture(name: string): string  // .xml file
function fixtureDir(): string                       // absolute path to fixtures dir
```

**Why:**
- TestServer: every e2e test (0xd.2, 0xd.3, 0xd.4, gwf.4, 8zf.3) needs to start the server. Without this, each test file bootstraps Express independently.
- Table-driven runner: instrument mechanics (30+ pitch position tests), LilyPond compilation (10+ template tests), music21 analysis (5+ MusicXML tests) are all naturally table-shaped. Writing describe/test/expect for each row is verbose. The runner generates one test per row from data.
- Fixture loader: all e2e tests reference the same fixture files (0xd.9). The loader provides a consistent API.

This infrastructure means tests are mostly DATA, not code. Adding coverage = adding rows to a table, not writing new test functions.

**YAGNI boundary:** No snapshot testing, no visual regression, no coverage reporting for v1. Just table-driven + server start/stop + fixtures.

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- TestServer starts, responds to requests, and shuts down cleanly
- Table-driven runner generates one named test per case
- Failed table test reports which row failed with readable output
- Fixture loader finds and reads files from test/fixtures/

**Test:** Self-hosting — the test infrastructure tests itself with a minimal example.

Implement the theory AgentTool<T> using tonal.js for instant music theory lookups.

**What:**
- Runs entirely in the browser — no fetch() to server
- Wraps tonal.js operations behind a unified tool interface
- Operations: interval (distance between notes), transpose (pitch by interval), chord_detect (identify chord from notes), chord_notes (spell chord), scale_notes (notes in scale), scale_chords (diatonic chords in key), roman_parse (Roman numeral → chord in key), enharmonic (equivalent spellings)
- Input: { operation: string, args: Record<string, any> }

**Implementation:**
```typescript
import { Note, Interval, Chord, Scale, Key, RomanNumeral } from 'tonal';

// Map operations to tonal.js calls
switch (params.operation) {
  case 'interval': return Interval.distance(args.from, args.to);
  case 'transpose': return Note.transpose(args.note, args.interval);
  case 'chord_detect': return Chord.detect(args.notes);
  // etc.
}
```

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- theory('interval', {from:'C4', to:'G4'}) → 'P5'
- theory('transpose', {note:'F#4', interval:'m3'}) → 'A4'
- theory('chord_detect', {notes:['C','E','G']}) → contains 'C' or 'CM'
- No server call made (verify in network tab or by testing offline)

**Test:**
- Test each operation with known input/output pairs
- Verify interval: C4 to G4 = P5
- Verify transpose: C4 + P5 = G4
- Verify chord_detect: [C,E,G] = C major
- Verify scale_chords: A minor returns Am, Bdim, C, Dm, Em, F, G

**What:** A factory that creates Express route handlers with consistent input validation, error handling, and response formatting.

```typescript
function createApiRoute<TInput, TOutput>(config: {
  validate: (body: unknown) => TInput;   // parse + validate, throws on bad input
  handler: (input: TInput) => Promise<TOutput>;
}): RequestHandler

// Usage:
app.post("/api/compile", createApiRoute({
  validate: (body) => Value.Decode(CompileParams, body),
  handler: async (input) => {
    const result = await runSubprocess({ command: "lilypond", ... });
    return parseCompileResult(result);
  }
}));
```

The factory handles:
- Input validation via the validate callback (TypeBox Value.Decode or custom)
- 400 response with structured error on validation failure
- try/catch around handler with 500 response on unhandled errors
- Consistent JSON response envelope: `{ ok: true, data }` or `{ ok: false, error }`
- Request logging (method, path, duration, status)

**Why:** 8+ Express routes all follow: validate body → try handler → JSON result → catch error. Without this: each route reimplements validation, error handling, and response formatting. With this: one ~40 LOC factory, each route is just validate + handler.

**YAGNI boundary:** No middleware composition, no auth (mTLS handles that at Traefik layer), no rate limiting for v1. Just validation + handler + error handling.

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- Valid input → handler runs → 200 with { ok: true, data }
- Invalid input → 400 with { ok: false, error: "..." }
- Handler throws → 500 with { ok: false, error: "..." }
- Duration logging on every request

**Test (table-driven):**
```typescript
const routeTests = [
  { name: "valid input", body: { source: "test" }, expectStatus: 200, expectOk: true },
  { name: "missing field", body: {}, expectStatus: 400, expectOk: false },
  { name: "handler error", body: { source: "test" }, handlerThrows: true, expectStatus: 500 },
];
// Use supertest with a minimal Express app
```

**What:** A class that wraps an InstrumentProfile and provides computational methods used by 5+ tools. This is the core domain model — the single place that knows how to navigate tunings, calculate positions, and check constraints.

```typescript
class InstrumentModel {
  constructor(profile: InstrumentProfile) {}

  // Core pitch ↔ position mapping (the heart of tabulate)
  positionsForPitch(pitch: string): TabPosition[]
  pitchAtPosition(course: number, fret: number): string

  // Course properties
  isFretted(course: number): boolean
  isDiapason(course: number): boolean
  isReentrant(course: number): boolean
  soundingPitch(course: number, fret: number): string  // accounts for re-entrant octave

  // Constraints
  maxStretch(): number           // 4 for lute, 5 for guitar
  maxFrets(): number
  courseCount(): number
  frettedCourseCount(): number

  // Voicing support
  voicingsForChord(pitches: string[], maxStretch?: number): Voicing[]

  // Diapason support (baroque lute / theorbo)
  diapasonPitches(scheme?: string): Map<number, string>
  setDiapasonScheme(key: string): void  // switch tuning scheme

  // Helpers
  distanceBetween(pos1: TabPosition, pos2: TabPosition): number  // fret span
  isPlayable(positions: TabPosition[]): { ok: boolean; violations: Violation[] }

  // Static factory
  static fromProfile(profile: InstrumentProfile): InstrumentModel
  static load(id: string): Promise<InstrumentModel>  // load profile + construct
}
```

**Why this is the biggest DRY win:**
- tabulate becomes: `model.positionsForPitch(params.pitch)` — the core logic lives here, not in the tool
- voicings becomes: `model.voicingsForChord(params.notes, params.max_stretch)` — cartesian product + filtering + ranking is here
- check_playability becomes: iterate bars, call `model.isPlayable(positions)` per beat
- transpose becomes: use pitch.ts to transpose, then `model.positionsForPitch()` to validate
- diapasons becomes: `model.diapasonPitches(params.key)` — pure lookup

Without InstrumentModel: each of those 5 tools reimplements profile navigation, pitch-to-fret calculation, diapason handling, re-entrant logic. That is ~100 LOC duplicated 5 times.
With InstrumentModel: one ~200 LOC class, tools become thin wrappers (~20 LOC each).

**Depends on:** xzu.1 (TypeBox schemas for TabPosition, Voicing, etc.), xzu.2 (pitch.ts for noteToMidi, transposeNote), jlj.2 (YAML profile loader)

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- positionsForPitch returns correct positions for all 7 instrument types
- Diapason courses return open-only positions
- Re-entrant courses account for octave displacement
- voicingsForChord filters by max_stretch and ranks correctly
- isPlayable catches stretch violations and same-course conflicts
- Diapason scheme switching works for all 5 standard baroque lute schemes

**Test (table-driven — this is where the real coverage lives):**
```typescript
const positionTests = [
  // Baroque lute
  { pitch: "F4", instrument: "baroque-lute-13", expected: [{ course: 1, fret: 0, quality: "open" }] },
  { pitch: "G4", instrument: "baroque-lute-13", expected: [{ course: 1, fret: 2, quality: "low_fret" }] },
  { pitch: "A2", instrument: "baroque-lute-13", expected: [{ course: 6, fret: 0, quality: "open" }] },
  { pitch: "G2", instrument: "baroque-lute-13", expected: [{ course: 7, fret: 0, quality: "diapason" }] },
  // Baroque guitar (re-entrant)
  { pitch: "D4", instrument: "baroque-guitar-5", stringing: "french",
    expected: [{ course: 2, fret: 3, quality: "low_fret" }, { course: 4, fret: 0, quality: "open" }] },
  // Classical guitar (straightforward)
  { pitch: "E2", instrument: "classical-guitar-6", expected: [{ course: 6, fret: 0, quality: "open" }] },
  // ... 30+ rows covering all instruments and edge cases
];

const voicingTests = [
  { notes: ["D3", "A3", "D4", "F4"], instrument: "baroque-lute-13", maxStretch: 4,
    expectMinVoicings: 1, expectNoSameCourse: true },
  // ...
];

const playabilityTests = [
  { positions: [{course:1,fret:0},{course:3,fret:5}], instrument: "baroque-lute-13",
    expectViolation: "stretch" },
  { positions: [{course:1,fret:2},{course:1,fret:3}], instrument: "baroque-lute-13",
    expectViolation: "same_course" },
  // ...
];
```

Implement custom tool renderers for visual feedback inline in the chat stream.

**What:**
Three renderers using pi-web-ui's registerToolRenderer():

1. **compile renderer:** If result.details.svg is present, render it as an inline SVG element in the chat. Wrap in a styled container with a border. On error, show error list as formatted text.

2. **fretboard renderer:** If result.details.svg is present, render the fretboard SVG diagram inline. Smaller than compile output — contained in a compact card.

3. **check_playability renderer:** Render violations as a styled list with icons (✓ for clean, ⚠ for violations). Show difficulty badge (beginner/intermediate/advanced).

**Implementation:**
```typescript
import { registerToolRenderer } from '@mariozechner/pi-web-ui';

registerToolRenderer('compile', {
  render(params, result) {
    if (result.details?.svg) {
      const el = document.createElement('div');
      el.className = 'compile-result';
      el.innerHTML = result.details.svg;
      return el;
    }
    return null; // fall back to text
  }
});
```

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- Compile results show SVG inline in chat
- Fretboard diagrams show inline
- Playability reports show structured violation list
- Renderers degrade gracefully (return null → default text rendering)

**Test:**
- Mock a compile result with SVG → verify renderer produces DOM element with SVG
- Mock a playability result with violations → verify DOM shows violation list
- Mock result with no details → verify null returned (text fallback)

Implement src/main.ts — the browser entry point that wires everything together.

**What:**
1. Fetch instrument profiles from /api/instruments
2. Build system prompt via buildSystemPrompt(instruments)
3. Register all tool renderers
4. Create Agent instance with all 10 tools and system prompt
5. Set up ChatPanel web component and connect to agent
6. Set up ArtifactsPanel (or div for artifacts)
7. Wire streamProxy to /api/stream

**Code structure (from SPEC.md):**
```typescript
import { Agent } from '@mariozechner/pi-agent-core';
import { ChatPanel, ArtifactsPanel, registerToolRenderer } from '@mariozechner/pi-web-ui';

// Register renderers
registerToolRenderer('compile', compileRenderer);

// Fetch profiles, build prompt
const instruments = await fetch('/api/instruments').then(r => r.json());
const agent = new Agent({
  initialState: {
    tools: [compileTool, tabulateTool, ...],
    systemPrompt: buildSystemPrompt(instruments),
  },
  streamProxy: '/api/stream',
});

const chatPanel = document.querySelector('chat-panel') as ChatPanel;
chatPanel.setAgent(agent);
```

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- Application loads in browser without errors
- ChatPanel renders and accepts user input
- Agent is configured with all 10 tools
- LLM calls are proxied through /api/stream
- Tool results render with custom renderers

**Test:**
- Load app in browser → verify chat panel visible
- Type a message → verify it reaches the agent (may need LLM key for full test)
- Verify all tools registered (agent.tools.length === 10)

**What:** Create src/types.ts with all shared TypeBox schemas and TypeScript interfaces used across tools and server endpoints.

**Schemas to define:**
- TabPosition: { course: number, fret: number, quality: "open" | "low_fret" | "high_fret" | "diapason" }
- Voicing: { positions: TabPosition[], stretch: number, campanella_score: number, open_strings: number }
- CompileError: { bar: number, beat: number, line: number, type: string, message: string }
- CompileResult: { svg?: string, pdf?: string, midi?: string, errors: CompileError[], barCount?: number, voiceCount?: number }
- Violation: { bar: number, type: "stretch" | "same_course" | "rh_pattern" | "out_of_range", description: string }
- PlayabilityResult: { violations: Violation[], difficulty: "beginner" | "intermediate" | "advanced", flagged_bars: number[] }
- LintViolation: { bar: number, beat: number, type: string, description: string, voices: string[] }
- AnalysisResult: { key: string, timeSignature: string, voices: VoiceRange[], chords: ChordAnalysis[] }
- InstrumentProfile: { id: string, name: string, courses/strings: number, tuning: TuningEntry[], frets: number, constraints: string[], notation: string, ... }
- All TypeBox parameter schemas for each tool (CompileParams, TabulateParams, VoicingsParams, etc.)

**Why:** Single source of truth for types shared between browser tools, server endpoints, and tool renderers. TypeBox schemas serve dual purpose: runtime validation (server) and type generation (TypeScript). Prevents type drift between client and server.

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- All schemas compile with `npx tsc --noEmit`
- Schemas are importable from both src/tools.ts and src/server/*.ts
- Each schema matches the tool parameter descriptions in SPEC.md exactly

**Test:**
- TypeScript compilation passes
- Import each schema in a test file and verify it matches expected shape
- Use TypeBox's Value.Check() to validate sample data against each schema

**What:** Small utility module with helpers used by every tool definition.

```typescript
// The universal result builder — used by every tool
function toolResult<T>(text: string, details: T): AgentToolResult<T> {
  return { content: [{ type: "text", text }], details };
}

// Error result builder
function toolError<T>(message: string): AgentToolResult<T> {
  return { content: [{ type: "text", text: `Error: ${message}` }], details: undefined as any };
}

// Common formatters for content text
function formatViolations(violations: LintViolation[]): string {
  if (violations.length === 0) return "No voice leading violations found. Passage is clean.";
  return `${violations.length} violation(s) found:\n` +
    violations.map(v => `  Bar ${v.bar}, beat ${v.beat}: ${v.description}`).join("\n");
}

function formatPositions(positions: TabPosition[]): string {
  return positions.map(p =>
    `Course ${p.course}, fret ${p.fret} (${p.quality})`
  ).join("\n");
}

function formatChordProgression(chords: ChordAnalysis[]): string {
  // Group by bar, format as "Bar N: I | V6 | vi | IV"
}
```

**Why:** Every tool returns `{ content: [{ type: "text", text }], details }`. That nested structure is 3 levels deep and easy to typo. `toolResult("text", data)` is a one-liner. The formatters (violations, positions, chords) are reused across multiple tools — lint+check_playability both format violations, tabulate+voicings both format positions.

Without this: 10 tools each construct the AgentToolResult manually + reimplement formatting.
With this: 10 one-liners + shared formatters.

**YAGNI boundary:** Only add formatters that serve 2+ tools. Do not pre-build formatters for hypothetical future tools.

**Acceptance Criteria:**
- toolResult produces valid AgentToolResult accepted by pi-agent-core
- toolError produces valid error result
- formatViolations handles 0, 1, and N violations
- formatPositions handles all quality types

**Test:**
```typescript
// Unit tests, not table-driven — these are trivial functions
test("toolResult", () => {
  const r = toolResult("hello", { value: 1 });
  expect(r.content[0].text).toBe("hello");
  expect(r.details.value).toBe(1);
});
```
